  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "India's bid to ban Masood Azhar, the leader of the Pakistan-based militant group Jaish-e-Mohammed, has faced challenges primarily due to China's opposition. As a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council (UNSC), China has the power to veto resolutions, and it has exercised this power to block India's attempts to designate Azhar as a terrorist.\n\nIf India were a permanent member of the UNSC, it would have greater influence and authority within the Council, which might have changed the dynamics of the situation. However, it is important to note that UNSC decisions often require the support of multiple other permanent members, and geopolitical relationships play a significant role in such matters. China has historically supported Pakistan for various strategic reasons, and it is uncertain whether India's presence as a permanent member would have been sufficient to overcome that.\n\nIn summary, even as a permanent member, India might still have faced considerable challenges in getting support for sanctioning Masood Azhar without addressing the underlying geopolitical considerations, particularly China's longstanding support for Pakistan.",
